<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,343,511,536]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
The dorsal pelage of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taylor &amp; Lavrenchenko &amp; Carleton &amp; Verheyen &amp; Bennett &amp; Oosthuizen &amp; Maree" authorityYear="2011" box="[594,748,512,536]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis box="[594,614,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[630,748,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is bright brown with a reddish shade. Ventral pelage is pale yellowish-grey, the individual hairs yellow tipped and grey at the base. The ears are blackish, their inner surface covered with short rufous hairs. The dorsal surface of the forefeet and hindfeet is dark grey; the claws are grey. The tail is relatively short (49.3% of HB). The caudal hairs are blackish on the upper surface and pale yellowish on the lower surface; however, the tail does not appear distinctly bicoloured.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,151,1472]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
The robust skull of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taylor &amp; Lavrenchenko &amp; Carleton &amp; Verheyen &amp; Bennett &amp; Oosthuizen &amp; Maree" authorityYear="2011" box="[414,565,692,716]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis box="[414,434,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[447,565,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[581,660,692,716]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="48.[151,249,1971,1994]" captionTargetBox="[196,1367,183,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-35@48.[196,1384,177,1946]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 17(a–c). Photographs comparing dorsal, ventral and lateral views of the skulls of holotype of Otomys yaldeni (ZMMU 162594)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280622" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280622/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) is reflected in the large means recorded for most cranial dimensions, which exceed those of all other representatives of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Bohmann" authorityYear="1952" box="[779,875,728,752]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="typus">
<emphasis box="[779,799,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[816,875,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">typus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex except for interorbital width (
<tableCitation box="[1332,1422,727,751]" captionStart="TABLE 9" captionStartId="52.[151,234,1198,1221]" captionText="TABLE 9. Summary statistics for taxa recognised by this study." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Table 9</tableCitation>
). Although the observed ranges of certain external and cranial variables overlap, four cranial variables do not overlap in size: GLS (
<quantity box="[308,473,799,823]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.575" metricValueMax="4.82" metricValueMin="4.33" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="45.75" valueMax="48.2" valueMin="43.3">43.3–48.2 mm</quantity>
versus 
<quantity box="[561,729,799,823]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.88" metricValueMax="4.33" metricValueMin="3.4299999999999997" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="38.8" valueMax="43.3" valueMin="34.3">34.3–43.3 mm</quantity>
); MXTL (11.0–12.0 mm versus 
<quantity box="[1096,1250,799,823]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.3" metricValueMax="10.5" metricValueMin="8.1" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="9.3" valueMax="10.5" valueMin="8.1">8.1–10.5 mm</quantity>
); NAW (8.0–9.0 mm versus 5.8–8.0 mm); PL (
<quantity box="[483,646,836,860]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4899999999999998" metricValueMax="2.62" metricValueMin="2.36" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="24.9" valueMax="26.2" valueMin="23.6">23.6–26.2 mm</quantity>
versus 
<quantity box="[731,894,836,860]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0149999999999997" metricValueMax="2.36" metricValueMin="1.67" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="20.15" valueMax="23.6" valueMin="16.7">16.7–23.6 mm</quantity>
) (
<tableCitation box="[916,1002,836,860]" captionStart="TABLE 9" captionStartId="52.[151,234,1198,1221]" captionText="TABLE 9. Summary statistics for taxa recognised by this study." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Table 9</tableCitation>
). The anterior face of the lower incisor has two well defined and equally deep grooves. The upper third molar has 8 or 9 complete laminae (
<quantity box="[1284,1327,871,895]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.286" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="in" value="9.0">9 in</quantity>
the 
<typeStatus pageId="43" pageNumber="44">holotype</typeStatus>
) and the lower first molar 4 complete laminae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1309,943,968]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,151,1472]" box="[197,1309,943,968]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,943,968]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from two localities in northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[904,1001,943,967]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
, 
<quantity box="[1012,1167,943,967]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="m" value="2300.0" valueMax="2500.0" valueMin="2100.0">2100–2500 m</quantity>
(see above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,151,1472]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,295,980,1004]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" reason="1">Ecology.</emphasis>
The type locality currently represents a true agricultural landscape, presumably much transformed from the time when Cheesman collected the series. The 
<typeStatus box="[790,885,1015,1039]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[941,1045,1016,1040]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">paratypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taylor &amp; Lavrenchenko &amp; Carleton &amp; Verheyen &amp; Bennett &amp; Oosthuizen &amp; Maree" authorityYear="2011" box="[1085,1238,1016,1040]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis box="[1085,1105,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1120,1238,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were supposedly collected in an intrazonal wetland habitat. The specimen from Debra Marcos (BMNH 70.657) was captured in low 
<taxonomicName box="[151,227,1088,1112]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,227,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
scrub. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taylor &amp; Lavrenchenko &amp; Carleton &amp; Verheyen &amp; Bennett &amp; Oosthuizen &amp; Maree" authorityYear="2011" box="[304,514,1088,1112]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis box="[304,514,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Otomys cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occupies lower elevations (
<quantity box="[823,976,1088,1112]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="m" value="2300.0" valueMax="2500.0" valueMin="2100.0">2100–2500 m</quantity>
) than other Ethiopian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1824" box="[1224,1309,1088,1112]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1224,1309,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Otomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(excluding the rainforest dweller 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[397,504,1124,1148]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fortior">
<emphasis box="[397,504,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">O. fortior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Nevertheless, habitat requirements of this new species remain unclear.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,151,1472]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,1160,1184]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
We selected the specific epithet to recognize Robert E. Cheesman (1878–1962), who collected the 
<typeStatus box="[151,249,1196,1220]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">holotype</typeStatus>
and topotypic series of this distinctive species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. Cuvier" authorityYear="1824" box="[801,886,1196,1220]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Otomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,886,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Otomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Cheesman was a British military and diplomatic officer in the Middle East, Arabian Peninsula, and nearby Africa, and like many other professionals of this era, he developed broad interests in the geography and natural history of the lands where he worked. During his service as Consul in North-West 
<collectingCountry box="[405,520,1304,1328]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Abyssinia</collectingCountry>
, Cheesman not only explored the source of the 
<collectingRegion box="[1056,1165,1304,1328]" country="Sudan" name="An Nil al Azraq" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Blue Nile</collectingRegion>
and surveyed its course from Lake Tana to 
<collectingCountry box="[364,475,1340,1364]" name="Sudan" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">the Sudan</collectingCountry>
border (
<emphasis box="[571,1138,1340,1364]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Lake Tana and the 
<collectingRegion box="[783,890,1340,1364]" country="Sudan" name="An Nil al Azraq" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Blue Nile</collectingRegion>
: An Abyssinian Quest
</emphasis>
by R. E. Cheesman, 1936; Macmillan: London, 400 pp.), but also found time to collect bird and mammal specimens for the British Museum. The species name combines the surname Cheesman and genitive singular case-ending “i” indicative of masculine gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
